  "What is the relationship between peak voltage and RMS voltage?": "",
  "V_rms = V₀ × √2": "",
  "V_rms = V₀ / √2": "",
  "V_rms = V₀ / 2": "",
  "V_rms = V₀ × 2": "",
  "V_rms = V₀/√2 ≈ 0.707 × V₀. This is the effective DC equivalent voltage for power calculations.": "",
  "What is the resonant frequency formula for an RLC circuit?": "",
  "f = 1/(2π√(LC))": "",
  "f = 2π√(LC)": "",
  "f = LC/(2π)": "",
  "f = 2πLC": "",
  "Resonance occurs when ω = 1/√(LC), giving f = 1/(2π√(LC)). At this frequency, X_L = X_C.": "",
  "What is 'alternating current' (AC)?": "",
  "Electric current that periodically reverses direction in a sinusoidal pattern": "",
  "Electric current that flows in one direction continuously without reversing": "",
  "Electric current that only flows when a switch is repeatedly turned on and off": "",
  "Electric current that gradually increases in strength over time without limit": "",
  "Alternating current periodically reverses direction, typically following a sinusoidal pattern. The voltage and current oscillate between positive and negative values.": "",
  "What does 'RMS' stand for and what does it represent?": "",
  "Root Mean Square — the effective DC equivalent value for power calculations": "",
  "Relative Maximum Signal — the highest voltage reached during a single cycle": "",
  "Resistance Measurement Standard — the standard way to measure AC resistance": "",
  "Rapid Mode Switching — how quickly AC changes between positive and negative": "",
  "RMS stands for Root Mean Square. It represents the equivalent DC value that would dissipate the same power in a resistor as the AC signal.": "",
  "What is 'reactance' in an AC circuit?": "",
  "The opposition to AC current from capacitors or inductors but not resistors": "",
  "The total opposition to current flow including resistance and all components": "",
  "The power dissipated as heat in a purely resistive AC circuit component": "",
  "The frequency at which an RLC circuit reaches its maximum current value": "",
  "Reactance is the opposition to AC current from capacitors (X_C = 1/(ωC)) or inductors (X_L = ωL). Unlike resistance, reactance depends on frequency and does not dissipate energy as heat.": "",
  "What is 'impedance' (Z) in an AC circuit?": "",
  "The opposition from resistance only, ignoring capacitors and inductors": "",
  "The total opposition to AC current combining resistance and reactance": "",
  "The power factor of the circuit relating real and apparent power": "",
  "The peak voltage divided by the peak current at any given moment": "",
  "Impedance is the total opposition to AC current: Z = √(R² + (X_L − X_C)²). It combines resistance (energy-dissipating) with reactance (energy-storing).": "",
  "What does 'resonance' mean in an RLC circuit?": "",
  "The frequency at which inductive and capacitive reactances are equal and cancel": "",
  "The frequency at which the circuit stops working and no current flows at all": "",
  "The frequency at which all energy is dissipated as heat in the resistor": "",
  "The frequency at which the voltage and current both drop to exactly zero": "",
  "Resonance occurs when X_L = X_C (ωL = 1/(ωC)). The reactances cancel, impedance is at its minimum (Z = R), and current is at its maximum.": "",
  "What is 'frequency' in the context of AC?": "",
  "The number of complete cycles of AC voltage or current per second in hertz": "",
  "The maximum voltage that the AC source can produce during each cycle": "",
  "The time it takes for one complete cycle of the alternating waveform": "",
  "The ratio of peak voltage to RMS voltage in an alternating current signal": "",
  "Frequency (f) is the number of complete cycles per second, measured in hertz (Hz). Standard household AC in the US is 60 Hz; in many other countries it is 50 Hz.": "",
  "What is the 'period' of an AC signal?": "",
  "The maximum amplitude of the voltage waveform measured from zero to peak": "",
  "The time for one complete cycle of the alternating voltage or current signal": "",
  "The total duration that AC power is supplied to a circuit before it stops": "",
  "The phase difference between voltage and current in an RLC circuit loop": "",
  "The period (T) is the time for one complete cycle: T = 1/f. For 60 Hz AC, T = 1/60 ≈ 0.0167 seconds.": "",
  "What is 'phase difference' in an AC circuit?": "",
  "The time delay between voltage and current waveforms expressed in degrees": "",
  "The difference in amplitude between the voltage and current peak values": "",
  "The difference in frequency between two AC signals in the same circuit": "",
  "The physical distance between two components connected in the circuit": "",
  "Phase difference is the angular offset between voltage and current waveforms. In a resistor it is 0°, in a capacitor current leads by 90°, and in an inductor current lags by 90°.": "",
  "What is 'capacitive reactance'?": "",
  "The opposition to AC current by a capacitor: X_C = 1/(ωC), decreasing with frequency": "",
  "The opposition to AC current by an inductor: X_L = ωL, increasing with frequency": "",
  "The DC resistance of a capacitor when connected to a direct current source": "",
  "The total impedance of a circuit containing only capacitors and no resistors": "",
  "Capacitive reactance X_C = 1/(ωC) = 1/(2πfC). It decreases as frequency increases because a capacitor passes high-frequency signals more easily.": "",
  "What is 'inductive reactance'?": "",
  "The opposition to DC current by an inductor in a circuit at zero frequency": "",
  "The energy stored in a capacitor's electric field during each AC cycle": "",
  "The total resistance of a coil including its wire resistance and inductance": "",
  "Inductive reactance X_L = ωL = 2πfL. It increases with frequency because the inductor opposes rapid changes in current more strongly.": "",
  "A student measures the peak voltage of an AC outlet as 170 V. What is the RMS voltage?": "",
  "The RMS voltage is approximately 85 V": "",
  "The RMS voltage is approximately 120 V": "",
  "The RMS voltage is approximately 170 V": "",
  "The RMS voltage is approximately 240 V": "",
  "V_rms = V₀/√2 = 170/1.414 ≈ 120 V. This is why US outlets are rated at 120 V — that is the RMS value.": "",
  "A student connects only a capacitor to an AC source and increases the frequency. What happens to the current?": "",
  "Current decreases because the capacitor blocks higher frequencies": "",
  "Current increases because capacitive reactance decreases with frequency": "",
  "Current stays constant regardless of the frequency of the AC source": "",
  "Current drops to zero because capacitors cannot pass alternating current": "",
  "X_C = 1/(2πfC). As frequency increases, X_C decreases, so more current flows. Capacitors pass high frequencies easily and block low frequencies.": "",
  "A student connects only an inductor to an AC source and increases the frequency. What happens to the current?": "",
  "Current increases because inductors pass higher frequencies more easily": "",
  "Current stays exactly the same at all frequencies for an inductor": "",
  "Current decreases because inductive reactance increases with frequency": "",
  "Current increases to infinity as the frequency approaches resonance": "",
  "X_L = 2πfL. As frequency increases, X_L increases, reducing current. Inductors block high frequencies and pass low frequencies — opposite behavior to capacitors.": "",
  "A student tunes a radio by adjusting a variable capacitor in an RLC circuit. What are they doing?": "",
  "Changing the resistance to filter out unwanted radio stations": "",
  "Changing the resonant frequency to match the desired station's broadcast frequency": "",
  "Increasing the power output of the radio to receive a stronger signal": "",
  "Adjusting the volume of the radio by changing the current through speakers": "",
  "Changing the capacitance changes the resonant frequency f = 1/(2π√(LC)). When the circuit's resonant frequency matches a station's broadcast frequency, maximum current flows, and that station is selected.": "",
