  "The capacitors inside the charger overheat from storing too much charge": "",
  "The AC from the wall outlet is inherently hot and transfers heat to charger": "",
  "The charger contains resistive components (including transformer windings and voltage regulators). Power dissipated in these components (P = I²R) is converted to heat, warming the charger.": "",
  "A student learns that power lines transmit electricity at very high voltages. Why is this more efficient?": "",
  "Higher voltage means higher frequency which travels faster through the wires": "",
  "Higher voltage allows lower current which reduces I²R power losses in the wires": "",
  "Higher voltage makes the wires stronger and less likely to break from weather": "",
  "Higher voltage is required because electricity cannot travel long distances at low voltage": "",
  "P = IV, so for the same power, higher voltage means lower current. Power loss in wires is P_loss = I²R, so lower current dramatically reduces energy wasted as heat in the transmission lines.": "",
